{{Infobox company | name = Maritime Electric | logo = Maritime Electric logo.gif | type = [[Subsidiary]] | genre = | fate = | predecessor = | successor = | foundation = {{Start date|1918}} | founder = | defunct = | location_city = [[Charlottetown]], [[Prince Edward Island]] | location_country = [[Canada]] | location = | locations = | area_served = Prince Edward Island | key_people = | industry = [[Energy]] | products = [[Electricity]] | services = | revenue = | operating_income = | net_income = | aum = | assets = | equity = | owner = | num_employees = | parent = [[Fortis Inc.]] | divisions = | subsid = | homepage = [http://www.maritimeelectric.com maritimeelectric.com] | footnotes = | intl = }}
'''Maritime Electric''' is the supplier of electricity in [[Prince Edward Island]], [[Canada]]. Maritime Electric is a [[public utility]], and is regulated the [[Prince Edward Island Regulatory and Appeals Commission|Island Regulatory and Appeals Commission]] (IRAC) under the Electric Power Act and the Renewable Energy Act.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.maritimeelectric.com/about_us/regulation/reg_regulations_on_pei.asp| title=Electricity Regulation on PEI| deadurl=yes| archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090503053208/http://www.maritimeelectric.com/about_us/regulation/reg_regulations_on_pei.asp| archivedate=2009-05-03| df=}}</ref> The utility operates two generating stations on the island: the [[Charlottetown Thermal Generating Station]] and the [[Borden Generating Station]].
On November 13, 2009, it was announced that the PEI government was in discussion with the province of [[Quebec]], with regard to providing electric power between the two provinces, which could lead to a long-term supply contract with [[Hydro-Québec]], the construction of a submarine transmission line linking PEI and the [[Magdalen Islands]], and, pending Fortis' involvement, the sale of Maritime Electric to Hydro-Québec.<ref>{{cite news|title=Quebec, P.E.I. talk power |first=Brent |last=Bundale |work=Telegraph-Journal |location=Saint John, N.B. |date=14 November 2009 |page=C1 |accessdate=2009-11-14 |url=http://telegraphjournal.canadaeast.com/front/article/856990 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20111001192129/http://telegraphjournal.canadaeast.com/front/article/856990 |archivedate=October 1, 2011 }}</ref> This followed the announcement of Hydro-Québec's proposed purchase of most of [[NB Power]]'s assets two weeks earlier<ref>{{cite news|title=Quebec, N.B. strike $4.8B deal for NB Power |work=Canadian Broadcasting Corporation |url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/new-brunswick/story/2009/10/29/nb-power-sale.html |date=October 29, 2009 |accessdate=2009-10-29 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091031195424/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/new-brunswick/story/2009/10/29/nb-power-sale.html |archivedate=October 31, 2009 }}</ref> (which failed in March 2010).<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.cbc.ca/canada/new-brunswick/story/2010/03/24/nb-nbpower-graham-1027.html |work=CBC News |title=Quebec balked at NB Power sale costs |date=March 24, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100327123508/http://www.cbc.ca/canada/new-brunswick/story/2010/03/24/nb-nbpower-graham-1027.html |archivedate=March 27, 2010 }}</ref>
