A '''metal-phenolic network''' is a supramolecular coordination structure which consists of metal [[Ion|ions]] and [[polyphenols]]. These materials were first reported by an Australian group at The [[University of Melbourne]]. MPN materials can be coated on versatile substrates to form [[Nanostructure|nanostructured]] films,<ref>{{Cite journal|url = http://science.sciencemag.org/content/341/6142/154.short|title = One-Step Assembly of Coordination Complexes for Versatile Film and Particle Engineering|journal = Science|issue = 12|doi = 10.1126/science.1237265|year = 2013|volume = |page = 154|pmid = |author1=Hirotaka Ejima |author2=Joseph J. Richardson |author3=Kang Liang |author4=James P. Best |author5=Martin P. van Koeverden |author6=Georgina K. Such |author7=Jiwei Cui |author8=Frank Caruso |bibcode=2013Sci...341..154E}}</ref> and the toolbox of metal ions has been further extended across the periodic table.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Guo|first1=Junling|last2=Ping|first2=Yuan|last3=Ejima|first3=Hirotaka|last4=Alt|first4=Karen|last5=Meissner|first5=Mirko|last6=Richardson|first6=Joseph J.|last7=Yan|first7=Yan|last8=Peter|first8=Karlheinz|last9=von Elverfeldt|first9=Dominik|last10=Hagemeyer|first10=Christoph E.|last11=Caruso|first11=Frank|title=Engineering Multifunctional Capsules through the Assembly of Metal-Phenolic Networks|journal=Angewandte Chemie International Edition|date=26 May 2014|volume=53|issue=22|pages=5546–5551|doi=10.1002/anie.201311136}}</ref> Unlike many other coating materials, which form [[Covalent bond|covalent bonds]] with specific [[Substrate (chemistry)|substrate molecules]], MPNs adsorb to a wide variety of surfaces due to [[Non-covalent interactions|noncovalent forces]].<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Ejima|first=Hirotaka|last2=Richardson|first2=Joseph J.|last3=Caruso|first3=Frank|date=2017-02-01|title=Metal-phenolic networks as a versatile platform to engineer nanomaterials and biointerfaces|url=http://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/S1748013216304108|journal=Nano Today|volume=12|pages=136–148|doi=10.1016/j.nantod.2016.12.012}}</ref> Due to their significant versatile coating and multifunctional properties, MPN-based materials has been one of the fastest growing fields in chemistry and materials science. The applications of MPN-based materials have been extended to a wide spectrum of fields, such as drug delivery, [[Microscopy|bioimaging]], and biotechnology. In 2016, the same group reported the new property of MPN (and [[Dopamine|polydopamine]]) in the particle assembly driven by polyphenol-based modular functionalization and interfacial molecular interactions.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Guo|first1=Junling|last2=Tardy|first2=Blaise L.|last3=Christofferson|first3=Andrew J.|last4=Dai|first4=Yunlu|last5=Richardson|first5=Joseph J.|last6=Zhu|first6=Wei|last7=Hu|first7=Ming|last8=Ju|first8=Yi|last9=Cui|first9=Jiwei|last10=Dagastine|first10=Raymond R.|last11=Yarovsky|first11=Irene|last12=Caruso|first12=Frank|title=Modular assembly of superstructures from polyphenol-functionalized building blocks|journal=Nature Nanotechnology|date=10 October 2016|doi=10.1038/nnano.2016.172|bibcode=2016NatNa..11.1105G}}</ref>

